From aa50c99d3f0b55831a465d8947c4731eb31aa0fd Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: vllm-shim <vllm-shim@local>
Date: Thu, 1 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 8/8] debug(quark): sample MoRI EP dispatch/combine I/O dump on
 real-data calls

The first iteration of this dump fired on the first eager EP call per
shape, which always hit the warmup batch with synthetic data. The
warmup batch is a poor witness for the K2.6 EP gibberish because its
routing distribution doesn't match decode (many tokens share top-k,
some PEs receive nothing, no per-row local-hit variation).

Add two env knobs and richer per-row output:

  VLLM_SHIM_MXFP4_DUMP_EP_AFTER=N  skip the first N eager calls per
                                   shape (default 0 = first-call dump).
                                   Set to ~10 to skip warmup and grab
                                   a real serving call.
  VLLM_SHIM_MXFP4_DUMP_EP_RUNS=M   fire on M consecutive calls after
                                   the skip (default 1).

Per-row dump now includes the remapped local_topk_ids alongside the
original global topk_ids, plus out_abs_mean AND out_abs_max so we can
distinguish three otherwise-confusable cases on a per-row basis:

  - row had no local hits, output is exactly 0  (correct)
  - row had local hits, output is non-zero      (correct, expected)
  - row had local hits, output is 0 or spikes   (real bug)

New aggregate line compares rows_with_local_hit (counted from the
sentinel pattern in local_topk_ids) against rows_nonzero_output. If
they match, the masking pipeline is internally consistent and the
bug is elsewhere (combine semantics, weight layout, or numerical
compounding). If they diverge, the bug is inside triton_mxfp4_moe and
the direction of divergence tells us which way (kernel dropping valid
entries vs sentinel/padding leaking through).

This replaces the now-dead "MoRI injects placeholder topk_ids"
hypothesis: reading mori-v1.1.1 EpDispatchIntraNodeKernel_body
confirmed the dispatch is a faithful copy, so the prior dump's
per-rank slot-8 differences are just atomic-counter token-arrival
ordering. New dump targets the next round of hypotheses: combine
contract mismatch and per-row mask consistency.
